<HEADLINE>
<P>
FIRE DOES $500,000 DAMAGE TO BRIDGE; 3 BOYS ARRESTED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Three youths are believed to have ignited a fire Saturday afternoon that caused 
about $500,000 damage to a bridge and roadway in San Marcos, authorities said 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
The youths, boys ranging in age from 10 to 13, were arrested Saturday by 
sheriff's arson investigators on suspicion of starting an unlawful fire, 
according to Sgt. Julie Sutton. 
</P>
<P>
Witnesses saw three young boys running from the area where a bridge on Valpreda 
Road near Mission Road was engulfed in flames, Sutton said. Sheriff's 
investigators found a large gasoline can near the fire's origin underneath the 
bridge. 
</P>
<P>
The boys told authorities that they emptied the can into a stream running 
underneath the bridge, Sutton said. One of the boys ignited the gasoline and 
the bridge, which was made of a combination of asphalt and timber, immediately 
caught fire. 
</P>
<P>
"It put out a pretty good column of smoke," said San Marcos Fire Capt. Michael 
Marks. No one was injured in the blaze and no vehicles were damaged, Marks 
said. The bridge, about 25 to 30-feet, is closed to traffic pending a 
structural analysis, Marks said. 
</P>
<P>
The boys were taken to the sheriff's substation in Vista and later released 
into the custody of their parents, Sutton said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
