<P>
U.S. ACTS TO CURB MISSILES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Bush Administration has decided to ban the sale to India of a sophisticated 
missile-testing device and has expressed concern to France about reports of an 
offer to sell advanced rocket technology to Brazil, U.S. officials said. The 
two steps reflect a toughening U.S. stand on the sale of sophisticated 
technology and know-how to Third World nations seeking to develop their own 
ballistic missiles. A license for the sale to India of a $1.2-million system 
used to put re-entry vehicles under simulated stress has been under debate for 
some time. The French-led consortium Arianespace reportedly has offered missile 
technology to Brazil if the Brazilians agree to use the Ariane rocket for two 
new communications satellites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
